RESERVED RIGHTS — EXPRESSION AND IMPLEMENTATION

The copyright holder reserves all rights in the expressive
implementation, source code, user interface, documentation,
prompt text, behavioral directives, schemas, character design,
voice design, terminology, project naming, and workflows as
expressed in this codebase, together with all associated Lorevox
materials. This License does not transfer or grant any of those
rights.

The following names and brand marks are reserved and not licensed
under any terms:
  - The name "Lorevox" and all associated brand names and marks
  - The name "Lori", the Lori interviewer persona, voice design,
    behavioral directives, and interview character
  - The name "Hornelore" and the Horne family R&D crucible
    branding (used by the family-locked downstream build)
  - Any other Lorevox-derived product names, sub-product names,
    or branded surfaces released by the copyright holder

The expressive embodiments of the following systems — that is,
the source code, prompt text, schemas, and documentation that
implement them in this codebase — are also part of the reserved
rights:
  - The Archive → History → Memoir three-layer architecture as
    expressed in this codebase
  - The runtime71 cognitive state system and its prompt
    composition pipeline
  - The multi-pass interview model (Pass 1 / Pass 2A / Pass 2B)
    and the Timeline Spine structure
  - The four-layer family-truth pipeline (shadow archive /
    proposal layer / human review / promoted truth)
  - The Cognitive Support Model and dementia-safe pacing ladder
    (protected silence intervals, invitational re-entry, no-
    correction posture)
  - The memoir schema and biographical data structures

(Note: copyright protects expressive implementation, not abstract
ideas or methodologies. Independently-developed implementations
of similar architectures by third parties are not within the
scope of these reservations; what is reserved is the expression
in this codebase and any derivative works of it.)

